Weeks ago, long before the news leaked to The Athletic or any defiant press
release was issued, Jimmy Pitaro visited Rob Manfred to deliver the news in=
 person that ESPN was likely going to opt out of the last three years of it=
s broadcast deal with Major League Baseball. The ESPN chairman didn=E2=80=
=99t want to get out of baseball entirely, but he did want to work out a de=
al that either resulted in a lower rights fee payment, or additional progra=
mming=E2=80=94like local rights streams or bringing back midweek games for =
linear
and streaming=E2=80=94for roughly the same amount, about $550 million per y=
ear.

=C2=A0

Pitaro and Manfred had always had a good working relationship. Indeed, the =
commissioner had hosted Pitaro=E2=80=99s senior executive team at the World=
 Series in October. But when Pitaro started to bring up potential contract =
changes, Manfred stopped him and indicated that he couldn=E2=80=99t be aske=
d for a chit he couldn=E2=80=99t deliver. Baseball=E2=80=99s owners,
after all, were already irritated with executives in Bristol. Back in 2021,=
 when it signed its current deal, ESPN gave up weekday MLB games, allowing =
the network to negotiate downward its $750 million per year deal to an aver=
age of $550 million. MLB couldn=E2=80=99t allow ESPN to negotiate a lower r=
ate again, especially not after Manfred and team owners watched ESPN pay ha=
ndsome increases to keep the NFL ($2.7 billion per year), NBA ($2.6 billion=
), and College Football Playoff ($1.3
billion).=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Plus, Manfred believed he had leverage. He and his team had been speaking w=
ith other mediacos and were optimistic that MLB would find other bidders=E2=
=80=94surely for 2028, when the league=E2=80=99s national rights deals with=
 Fox and Warner Bros. Discovery expire. To that end, MLB has been talking t=
o streamers like Amazon and Netflix, and has had informal talks with offici=
als from Skydance, which is in the process of buying
CBS (and streamer Paramount+). NBC has shown some interest as well. In any =
event, it appeared that MLB was keen to establish relationships with more m=
edia companies in advance of 2028, even if it meant accepting lower rights =
fees for the next few years. But Manfred was not going to take a lowball bi=
d from ESPN back to his owners.

