QyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjA5MzgwNH0/9958f3c0b24977a657c7a630ccdaced9f643e=
8b12b545c11bfa7dde535568d44" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d400=
00;">podcast</a>. Frankly, I was surprised that she didn=E2=80=99t dismiss =
it outright. =E2=80=9CWhen you=E2=80=99ve got two Hall of Famers opining no=
t only about the history of college basketball, but the <em>future</em> of =
college basketball, you have to
listen,=E2=80=9D Ackerman told me. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve got some related =
ideas that we=E2=80=99re hatching here about alliances, about who we should=
 be working with, as we look to secure not only the future of the Big East,=
 but the future of college basketball.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Ackerman brought u=
p the =E2=80=9CChallenge=E2=80=9D games that the Big East used to play agai=
nst teams from the Big Ten and Big 12. =E2=80=9CThere have been conversatio=
ns about what we could all be doing together =E2=80=A6 to make sure college=
 basketball stays strong and relevant, as
football interests continue to dominate much of the headlines and much of t=
he bandwidth of the leagues that we consider peer conferences.=E2=80=9D</li=
><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Conference realignment promiscuity</e=
m>: Ackerman also addressed future conference realignment=E2=80=94a subject=
 that hits close to home for her given UConn=E2=80=99s recent discussions a=
bout a move to the Big 12. =E2=80=9CI will be curious to see over time how =
enlarged conferences continue to evolve relative to geography, and what
cross-country travel will mean long term for athletes who play multiple gam=
es a week,=E2=80=9D Ackerman said. =E2=80=9CIs that a sustainable model for=
 student athlete well-being? Remains to be seen.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Ackerman=
 told me she=E2=80=99s had conversations about West Coast schools joining t=
he Big East. =E2=80=9CGeography has always gotten in the way for us,=E2=80=
=9D she said. =E2=80=9CNobody wanted to take on the cross-country travel th=
