"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#3=
9;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:=
150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">Weeks ago, long before the news leaked to The Athletic or a=
ny defiant press
release was issued, <strong>Jimmy Pitaro</strong> visited <strong>Rob</stro=
ng> <strong>Manfred</strong> to deliver the news in person that ESPN was li=
kely going to opt out of the last three years of its broadcast deal with Ma=
jor League Baseball. The ESPN chairman didn=E2=80=99t want to get out of ba=
seball <em>entirely</em>, but he did want to work out a deal that either re=
sulted in a lower rights fee payment, or additional programming=E2=80=94lik=
e local rights streams or bringing back midweek games for linear
and streaming=E2=80=94for roughly the same amount, about $550 million per y=
ear.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Pitaro and Manfred had always had a good working r=
elationship. Indeed, the commissioner had hosted Pitaro=E2=80=99s senior ex=
ecutive team at the World Series in October. But when Pitaro started to bri=
ng up potential contract changes, Manfred stopped him and indicated that he=
 couldn=E2=80=99t be asked for a chit he couldn=E2=80=99t deliver. Baseball=
=E2=80=99s owners,
after all, were already irritated with executives in Bristol. Back in 2021,=
 when it signed its current deal, ESPN gave up weekday MLB games, allowing =
the network to negotiate downward its $750 million per year deal to an aver=
age of $550 million. MLB <em>couldn=E2=80=99t</em> allow ESPN to negotiate =
a lower rate again, especially not after Manfred and team owners watched ES=
PN pay handsome increases to keep the NFL ($2.7 billion per year), NBA ($2.=
6 billion), and College Football Playoff ($1.3
billion).=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;">Plus, Manfred believed he had leverage. He and his team h=
ad been speaking with other mediacos and were optimistic that MLB would fin=
d other bidders=E2=80=94surely for 2028, when the league=E2=80=99s national=
 rights deals with Fox and Warner Bros. Discovery expire. To that end, MLB =
has been talking to streamers like Amazon and Netflix, and has had informal=
 talks with officials from Skydance, which is in the process of buying
CBS (and streamer Paramount+). NBC has shown some interest as well. In any =
event, it appeared that MLB was keen to establish relationships with more m=
edia companies in advance of 2028, even if it meant accepting lower rights =
fees for the next few years. But Manfred was not going to take a lowball bi=
d from ESPN back to his owners.</p></div>
